  <section id="sanctions-impact" class="sec">
    <h2>5. Sanctions &amp; Economic Impact</h2>
    <p class="sec-lead">
      US sanctions have been one of the defining forces shaping Venezuela&rsquo;s
      economy since 2017, constricting trade, investment, and access to the
      international financial system.
    </p>

    <h3>The sanctions regime</h3>
    <p>
      The US imposed progressively broader sanctions on Venezuela between 2015
      and 2019, culminating in Executive Order 13884 (August 2019), which imposed
      a comprehensive block on the Government of Venezuela&mdash;one of the most
      sweeping sanctions programs in US history, comparable in scope to the
      programs on Cuba, Iran, and North Korea.
    </p>

    <h3>Economic impact</h3>
    <p>
      The economic effects of sanctions are intertwined with (and often difficult
      to separate from) the effects of economic mismanagement. Key impacts
      include:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Trade constriction:</strong> Venezuelan oil exports to the US
        dropped from ~500,000 bpd (2018) to effectively zero (2020&ndash;22),
        forcing crude into discounted sales to China, India, and intermediaries.</li>
      <li><strong>FDI collapse:</strong> Foreign direct investment fell to near
        zero. International companies wrote off Venezuelan assets or maintained
        minimal presence pending sanctions relief.</li>
      <li><strong>Financial isolation:</strong> Venezuelan entities lost access
        to the US banking system, correspondent banking relationships, and
        dollar-clearing infrastructure. Even non-US banks de-risked Venezuelan
        exposure.</li>
      <li><strong>Humanitarian concerns:</strong> UN agencies and humanitarian
        organizations documented the compounding effects of sanctions on an
        already-devastated economy, including reduced imports of food, medicine,
        and spare parts for essential services.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Post-transition recalibration (2026)</h3>
    <p>
      Following the January 2026 political transition, the US has significantly
      recalibrated its sanctions posture. General Licenses 50A (oil operations)
      and 52 (new investment) have reopened most commercial activity with the
      transitional government. However, individual sanctions remain on former
      regime officials, and the underlying executive orders have not been
      revoked. Full normalization depends on sustained democratic progress.
    </p>

    <p>
      <a href="/why-is-venezuela-sanctioned" style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--sr-blue);">
        Read our complete explainer: Why Is Venezuela Sanctioned? &rarr;
      </a>
    </p>
  </section>

  {# ======================================================================= #}
  <section id="labor" class="sec">
    <h2>6. Labor Market &amp; Migration</h2>
    <p class="sec-lead">
      Venezuela&rsquo;s labor market has been reshaped by the largest refugee
      crisis in the Western Hemisphere. The emigration of 7.7 million
      Venezuelans has created severe skills shortages across every sector.
    </p>

    <h3>Migration by the numbers</h3>
    <div class="card-grid cols-2">
      <div class="card">
        <div class="meta">Displacement</div>
        <h3>7.7 million</h3>
        <div class="row"><strong>Period</strong>2015&ndash;2024</div>
        <div class="row"><strong>Share</strong>~21% of pre-crisis population</div>
        <div class="row"><strong>Top destinations</strong>Colombia (2.9M), Peru (1.5M), US (545K+), Chile (444K)</div>
        <div class="note">Source: UNHCR/IOM R4V Response for Venezuelans platform (Dec 2024).</div>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="meta">Brain drain</div>
        <h3>Skilled labor exodus</h3>
        <div class="row"><strong>Physicians</strong>~40,000 left (est. 55% of total)</div>
        <div class="row"><strong>Engineers</strong>Petroleum engineers particularly affected</div>
        <div class="row"><strong>Educators</strong>~150,000 teachers emigrated</div>
        <div class="note">The loss of skilled professionals is one of the most significant long-term constraints on economic recovery.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Domestic labor market</h3>
    <p>
      Formal unemployment statistics in Venezuela are unreliable (the last
      official BCV labor survey was published in 2016). Independent estimates
      from Encovi (Encuesta Nacional de Condiciones de Vida) suggest:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Informal economy:</strong> Approximately 60% of the workforce
        operates in the informal sector, up from ~40% pre-crisis</li>
      <li><strong>Public sector wages:</strong> The minimum wage remains the
        equivalent of $3&ndash;5/month, rendering public-sector employment
        essentially untenable without supplementary income</li>
      <li><strong>Dollar economy:</strong> Workers in the dollarized formal
        sector (oil, telecoms, multinational operations) earn $200&ndash;800/month,
        creating stark inequality with bol&iacute;var-paid workers</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>TPS and the US connection</h3>
    <p>
      Approximately 600,000+ Venezuelans in the United States held Temporary
      Protected Status (TPS), which provided work authorization and protection
      from deportation. The program&rsquo;s evolution under the current US
      administration has significant implications for remittance flows to
      Venezuela, estimated at $4&ndash;5 billion annually.
    </p>

    <p>
      <a href="/tps-venezuela" style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--sr-blue);">
        Read our TPS Venezuela guide &rarr;
      </a>
    </p>
  </section>

