  <section id="investment" class="sec">
    <h2>7. Investment Climate</h2>
    <p class="sec-lead">
      Venezuela&rsquo;s investment environment is undergoing its most significant
      transformation since the Ch&aacute;vez-era nationalizations. The 2026
      political transition has created an opening&mdash;but risks remain
      substantial.
    </p>

    <h3>Foreign Direct Investment trends</h3>
    <p>
      FDI into Venezuela collapsed from $2.2 billion in 2014 to effectively
      zero during the peak sanctions period (2019&ndash;2022). Since the issuance
      of GL 50A and GL 52, preliminary data suggests a recovery to an estimated
      $1.5&ndash;2.5 billion in 2026, primarily concentrated in the oil and gas
      sector (Chevron, Repsol, Eni).
    </p>

    <h3>Key reforms under the Rodriguez administration</h3>
    <p>
      The transitional government has moved quickly to signal an
      investment-friendly posture:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Hydrocarbon law reform:</strong> IOC operatorship, reduced
        royalties, 40-year contracts, international arbitration</li>
      <li><strong>FX liberalization:</strong> The BCV has moved toward a
        managed-float exchange rate, reducing the multiple exchange-rate
        distortions that plagued the economy</li>
      <li><strong>Property rights signals:</strong> The government has expressed
        willingness to negotiate settlements for assets expropriated under
        Ch&aacute;vez and Maduro, though no formal framework has been established</li>
      <li><strong>Anti-corruption measures:</strong> An anti-corruption commission
        has been established, though its independence and effectiveness remain
        untested</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Sector opportunities</h3>
    <div class="card-grid cols-2">
      <div class="card">
        <div class="meta">Energy</div>
        <h3>Oil &amp; Gas</h3>
        <div class="note" style="border:0;padding:0;">
          The most immediate opportunity. Existing JV structures, GL 50A/52
          authorization, reformed fiscal terms. Chevron&rsquo;s expansion
          demonstrates viability. Requires OFAC compliance infrastructure.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="meta">Resources</div>
        <h3>Mining</h3>
        <div class="note" style="border:0;padding:0;">
          Venezuela has significant gold, iron ore, bauxite, coltan, and diamond
          deposits. The Arco Minero del Orinoco concession zone covers 112,000
          km&sup2;. Environmental and governance risks are extreme.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="meta">Property</div>
        <h3>Real Estate</h3>
        <div class="note" style="border:0;padding:0;">
          Caracas commercial real estate trades at deep discounts to comparable
          Latin American markets. Residential demand is rising with dollarization.
          Title certainty and expropriation risk are key concerns.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="meta">Agriculture</div>
        <h3>Agriculture</h3>
        <div class="note" style="border:0;padding:0;">
          Venezuela has 30+ million hectares of arable land, much of it
          underutilized. Domestic food production collapsed during the crisis,
          creating import-substitution opportunities in grains, livestock, and
          processed foods.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Major risks</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>FX controls:</strong> While liberalized, the BCV retains
        authority to reimpose capital controls. Profit repatriation mechanisms
        remain untested for new entrants.</li>
      <li><strong>Legal uncertainty:</strong> Venezuela&rsquo;s judiciary remains
        unreformed. Contract enforcement, property rights, and dispute resolution
        are unreliable outside of ICSID/ICC arbitration frameworks.</li>
      <li><strong>Sanctions compliance:</strong> US persons must maintain robust
        OFAC compliance programs. All general licenses are revocable. Counterparty
        screening against the SDN list is mandatory.</li>
      <li><strong>Political risk:</strong> The transitional government lacks
        electoral legitimacy. Maduro loyalists retain influence. A political
        reversal could undo reforms.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
