    <h3>IMF &amp; World Bank projections</h3>
    <p>
      The IMF&rsquo;s April 2026 <em>World Economic Outlook</em> projects
      Venezuelan real GDP growth of 4&ndash;6% for 2026 and 3&ndash;5% for 2027.
      The World Bank&rsquo;s <em>Global Economic Prospects</em> (June 2025
      update) is slightly more conservative, projecting 3.5&ndash;4.5% growth,
      citing political uncertainty as the primary downside risk.
    </p>
    <p>
      Both institutions note that the outlook is heavily contingent on: (1) the
      sustainability of the political transition; (2) continued sanctions relief;
      and (3) the pace of oil-sector capital deployment. A return to maximum
      sanctions pressure would likely push growth negative within 12&ndash;18
      months.
    </p>

    <h3>Key indicators to watch</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Oil production:</strong> Monthly OPEC data; target is 1.3M+ bpd by year-end</li>
      <li><strong>Inflation:</strong> BCV monthly CPI releases; breaking below 100% would be a milestone</li>
      <li><strong>OFAC actions:</strong> Any modification, expansion, or revocation of GL 50A/52</li>
      <li><strong>Election timeline:</strong> Credible commitment to internationally supervised elections</li>
      <li><strong>BCV reserves:</strong> Foreign-exchange reserves (currently ~$10B); reserve accumulation signals stability</li>
      <li><strong>Chevron production:</strong> Quarterly earnings for JV production data</li>
    </ul>
